Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port. Then hand that client to the MCP C# SDK's transport.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol  # MCP C# SDK
```

### Example test

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient wired to the
        // in-memory test server — no real port, no real server.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use StreamableHttpClientTransport, passing in the test client
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                // Name shown during initialization
                Name = "integration-test"
            },
            httpClient          // ← the in-memory client
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(
            transport,
            cancellationToken: CancellationToken.None
        );

        // Now exercise the real MCP protocol
        var tools = await mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                Name = "integration-test"
            },
            httpClient
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await mcpClient.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" }
        );

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected-output", result.Content[0].Text);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your `Program` in-process; HTTP never hits the network |
| **Full protocol fidelity** | The MCP SDK client does real SSE/HTTP negotiation through the same middleware pipeline your production server uses |
| **Transport choice** | Use `SseClientTransport` for SSE-based servers, or `StreamableHttpClientTransport` if your server uses the newer Streamable HTTP transport — both accept an `HttpClient` |
| **Make `Program` visible** | Add `public partial class Program { }` to the bottom of your `Program.cs` if it uses top-level statements |

This gives you true end-to-end MCP protocol coverage (initialize → list → call → shutdown) with the speed of an in-memory test.
